How to Make DIY Candles // I recently made a big batch of candles for the teachers at my son’s school. And they turned out cute, so I updated my DIY candle guide and thought I would share the tutorial here too. Save this to reference back to for candle making later. 
🕯💛
1. Add a few inches of water to a large pot and turn on the stove to medium heat. Then, pour soy wax flakes, beads, or slabs into a pouring pot and put the pouring pot into the larger pot of water – double boiler style.
.
2. As the wax starts melting, stir every so often until it has melted completely and the melted soy wax is transparent. Then remove from heat and let the wax cool for a few minutes. This is when you would add a scent and color if desired.
.
3. While you are waiting for the wax to cool, add a wick to each container. Then it’s time to pour the wax. Quick note: Def wait for the wax to set up completely before moving or handling it at all.
.
4. Trim the wick down to 1/4 inch. Then, it’s ready to use.
.
And that’s it. :) For a WAY more detailed candle making tutorial (including how to make the tops of your candle perfectly smooth and all the supplies you’ll need), head to link in bi0. #candleaddiction #organicmodern #uniquepottery #modernorganic #handmadepottery

How we made a DIY bookcase / built in. Save this post for future DIY furniture inspo. 📚🔨 Before I get into it though… Jeff took the lead on this one and I helped where ever I could. That’s why I’m saying ‘we’ so much here. Didn’t want anyone to think it was weird. ANYWAY! The bookshelf is made of white oak ply (sheets of plywood with a white oak veneer on top and bottom) and I’ll do a budget breakdown of all the materials on stories today. Here’s how we made the bookcase…
.
📐Figure out the basic measurements for the build. Depth, length, and height. And then you can draw out your design or use something like Shapr3D to model it. After that, we used a site called Cut List optimizer to plan out the cuts we needed. This helped a lot to figure out how many sheets of plywood to order. 
.
🪚Make all of your cuts with a circular saw and straight edge (or you can use a track saw or table saw). 
.
🌙 Edge banding is next. You can edge band all of the exposed edges (that will be seen in the completed project) before assembly, except for any areas that need to be edge-banded with a miter cut detail. Do those after assembly. We used an iron on edge banding. You use the heat of the iron to attach it to the edges and then press down with a solid / flat surface and then a trimmer to remove any excess.
.
👋 Assembly. We used pocket holes for any shelves that had backs on them and then just screwed up from the bottom anywhere pocket holes wouldn’t work. Using a Kreg jig for the pocket holes makes things a lot easier.
. 
🔧 We added adjustable feet to the bottom of the bookcase shelving and the cabinet area. And then when it was all installed, we just covered it with a long white oak toe kick (using scrap wood leftover from the project). We stained all of the wood with Rubio Monocoat (color Pure).
.
✨ Then installed everything in the room, added the toe kick and attached the two pieces (bookshelf side and cabinet side) together and to the wall.
.
It’s hard to share lots of lengthy details here, so I have a more detailed tutorial on Paper and Stitch. And shared all the mistakes we made along the way as well. Lmk if you have any questions I can answer here though.

DIY Redo. Made a wood makeup organizer in 2016 and wanted to redo it, now that I have more experience with power tools and all of that. The new one is made of white oak and I’m using it mostly for art supplies rn. Here’s how to make your own…
.
✏️Determine how long and tall you want the piece to be and the cut the wood down to size. I only used 2 pieces of wood bc the wood was p thick already. But if you’re using a thinner wood, you may want more layers.
.
🧰Next, give each piece a light sanding or a more heavy duty sanding if needed. Then wipe the wood clean with a dry rag.
.
🗜️Glue up the pieces of wood, stack them together, and once they’re all aligned, clamp them together using 2-3 clamps, for several hours.
.
🪛Once the glue is dry, mark where you want the holes to be and use a drill bit, spade bit, and/ or forstner drill bit to make the holes, making sure not to go all the way through the bottom.
.
🪚Sand again if necessary and cut the legs. I used a thick dowel for the legs and cut it in half with a pull saw. Sand the legs after cutting if needed.
.
🗜️Glue and clamp the legs. Once dry, it’s ready to use. 
.
✨For a more detailed tutorial and the list of supplies, head to Paper and Stitch. And lmk what you think. Would you use this for makeup brushes or art supplies?

I’m sure some people won’t like this, but I painted our bathroom floor. I promise the before looked worse in person and I just HAD to stop looking at it. We didn’t have the budget to replace the tile either. So! Here’s how I painted the river rock flooring in my guest bathroom. 👩‍🎨
.
1️⃣ I swept the floors really well and then used a degreaser. I like Krud Kutter (cleans and degreases at the same time).
.
2️⃣ For the paint, I used a Rustoleum Home Floor Coating Kit - comes with paint and a separate sealant / top coat. I applied the base coat with a brush. I mostly did 1-2 foot areas at a time before pausing on the brushing and switching to a rag.
.
3️⃣ While the paint was still wet, I went back with a rag and patted over the surface gently to pull up some of the paint / remove any brushstrokes. I think this really helped get more depth of color in the floors and let some of the original rock colors come through. So don’t skip this step if you have river rock floors.
.
4️⃣ Repeat steps 2 and 3 until the entire floor is covered. Wait for the floor to dry according to the instructions on the paint you are using.
.
5️⃣ Once the floor is dry enough to add the top coat (according to instructions on packaging), use a roller or brush to paint the top coat over the base coat layer. If you’re using the same floor coating as me, it says to apply the top coat six hours after applying the base coat. And it also recommends two coats. *Wait for the floor to fully dry before walking on it, according to the instructions on the can. 
.
If you got this far, you must really like DIYs. So we should Send this to that friend who’s always doing some kind of DIY house project. 🤪
.
.
.
Budget-friendly DIY house project - tutorial for how to paint river rock flooring. #paintedfloors #bathroommakeover #budgetrenovation

I made these paint palettes for Hayes, but now I’m using them more than he is. 🎨👩‍🎨 Here’s how to make air dry clay paint palettes AND how to waterproof them. ✨Save this post if you want to make these for yourself (or your kids).✨Would be a good summertime craft imo.
.
1️⃣ Roll a palm size amount of clay into a ball and then roll it out with a rolling pin. Try and keep the thickness to about a 1/2 inch or thinner.
.
2️⃣ Carve out the outer paint palette shape.
You can use a popsicle stick, wooden skewer, or clay carving tool to cut the rolled out clay into the desired paint palette shape. Cookie cutters work too.
.
3️⃣ Dip your fingers into a little water and rub the edges of your shape to get rid of any jaggedness and smooth the surface.
.
4️⃣ Carve the interior paint well shapes (you can use your fingers, a carving tool, even a plastic spoon. Smooth the surface again, with your wet fingertips.
.
5️⃣ Let it dry overnight and make sure air is getting to all sides. You can use a cooling rack (like the ones for cookies) or something similar.
.
6️⃣ Once dry, smooth any areas that are still rough with sandpaper.
.
7️⃣ The last step is sealing. You need to seal the ENTIRE paint palette – top, sides, and back. Multiple times. So that when you wash the paint off, after each use, the air dry clay is protected from water. For sealing, you can use an acrylic sealer, clear polyurethane varnish, or my preferred method: which is 2-3 coats of clear nail polish (like a clear top coat). I did a layer or varnish first and then 2 coats of clear nail polish top coat. 
.
.
.
Clay paint palette DIY for creative kids and adults. Would be a great summer project to encourage creativity in kids. #kidscraftideas #airdryclaycreation #diyforkids #summercrafts

Whenever I see larger DIY projects and renovation stuff, I always wonder how much they really cost. 🤑 Sometimes DIYs are super affordable and other times, they're REALLY not. So today, I'm breaking down the costs for the built-in bookcase that we (Jeff and I) made for the office…
🔨
White oak veneer plywood sheets $200 each x 4 = $800
white oak edge banding $70
Stain and accelerator $60
adjustable bookcase feet $30
screws and misc $25
🧰
TOTAL: $985 Was the final cost more or less than you thought it would be?
🪚
Could it have been cheaper? YES! If we would have used a different kind of wood (like regular plywood for example), the total cost of the project would have been less than $300. It was worth it (for us) to splurge on white oak, but using regular plywood and painting it the same color as the walls would be a good cost-saving option. Have any questions about this project? Lmk. I have a more detailed post on Paper and Stitch too - search 'built in' and it's the first result.
.
.

✨ Zero Dollar DIY: Cereal Box Art ✨ Made  these little DIY art pieces with Hayes, but there are so many more things you can make with cereal boxes and I’m sharing a bunch! ✂️Save this post so you can reference it later. 🎨 Here are 9 more ways you can use cereal boxes for crafting…
.
.
.
1️⃣Cereal box dollhouse DIY: I started one of these a couple of weeks ago with Hayes (haven’t finished yet). Cut the front off of a cereal box and leave the rest intact. Then hot glue, paint, add some roof shingles, and some dollhouse furniture made of recycled materials.
.
2️⃣Cereal box planters: Cut off the bottom of a cereal box, paint the outside, and fill the inside with soil and seeds for a window garden or full grown mini plants. You can also add a plastic bag liner if you want.
.
3️⃣Cereal box watch + bracelets: You can also make these with toilet paper holders. Just cut strips to use as the watch band or bracelet. Create a watch face in the shape of a circle, decorate it, and glue it all together. Add a tiny piece of velcro to the band as a final touch.
.
4️⃣DIY Notebooks: Just like the ones from the very end of the video. These are so easy to make with some cardboard, paint supplies, scrap paper, and a stapler.
.
5️⃣ Organizer: Cut a cereal box at an angle to resemble the shape of a file folder holder or magazine holder box. Cover it with scrap fabric or paint, and use it in the office or for papers and craft supplies.
.
6️⃣ Puzzles: Cut up leftover cereal box art into 10-20 pieces, mix ‘em up, and you have a puzzle.
.
7️⃣ Cereal box birdhouse DIY: A milk jug might be a little easier for a DIY birdhouse, but you can make one with cardboard too. Just might take a little more work and some extra glue.
.
8️⃣ Picture frames: This a cute way to frame artwork or photos. Add a magnet to the back and you can put it on the fridge.
.
9️⃣ Bookmarks: Just cut some strips. Paint, draw, or decorate the front and back. Add a hole to the top with a hole punch. And string a ribbon or piece of yarn through.
. 
Have any other cardboard ideas I missed? Lmk on the comments.

DIY headboard refresh. I made this arch headboard a few years ago and have been wanting to change the color for a while now. So I dyed an old duvet and used it to reupholster what I already had. 🛏️ Save this post for your next upholstery project. ✨ My top 5 upholstery tips below...

1️⃣ It can be difficult to find fabric by the yard, at a craft store, for example, that is long enough on all sides to upholster a headboard of this size. Using bed sheets or old duvet covers that are the same size as your mattress however, should be more than enough fabric for something like this.

2️⃣ You can dye natural fibers (like linen) very easily at home, even if the fabric is not white. I dyed my tan / beige duvet and the color turned out so pretty. The color of the fabric will likely not be exactly the same as what appears on the bottle. But if you dye small scraps ahead of time, you’ll know what to expect.

3️⃣ If you’re creating your headboard for the first time and not just refreshing the fabric with a new layer, be sure to add upholstery foam AND batting underneath.

4️⃣ Pull the fabric as tightly as you can when stapling. I usually do a handful of staples on one side and then pull the fabric toward the opposite side and staple there. And I do that again and again.

5️⃣ And lastly, a good stapler will save you a lot of time in the long run and the bad ones are almost the same price as the good ones anyway, so might as well get the best. I have tried MANY staplers over the years and the best one I’ve found for upholstery so far is the Dewalt Heavy Duty Stapler.

#organicmodern #bedroomrenovation #diyheadboard #reupholstery

I’ve never carved anything before, so might as well give it a try. I made this small wooden bowl and I think I might have a new hobby. Save this post for your next weekend DIY to try. 

🪚 Cut a block of soft wood (balsa or basswood) down with a saw. 

🥣 Carve the interior and exterior of the bowl. I started with the inside and then worked my way to outside. I used one gouge for all of the carving bc I didn’t want to invest in a ton of tools yet. It can be done with just one gouge. BUT a bent gouge or spoon gouge would have been a good addition (for cutting away material in the interior of the bowl.

✨ Once I had the majority of the bowl carved, I used a power sander to smooth the exterior and shape it a bit more (used 120 grit sandpaper). And then for the interior of the bowl, I sanded by hand with 120 grit. If you have a small Dremel with a sanding attachment, that would be ideal. But I don’t have one.

👍 Then I carved some more, sanded some more, and stained / sealed the wood.

So I found a 3 legged coffee table that I really love, but the price (over $4,000) is definitely out of reach atm. So I repurposed our coffee table and made my own for $67. ✨ Once I found the right size dowels (from a hardwood store), it all came together really fast…

1 I removed the base from the old coffee table.

2 Sanded the table top, cut the 3 legs down to size with a miter saw, and then sanded the legs.

3 Next, I attached the dowels to slightly larger pieces of wood, so that I could then drill into the underside of the table top and secure the legs.

4 Then I conditioned the wood (tabletop and legs). Any wood conditioner is fine.

5 Last step was staining the wood. I used a gel stain this time bc I already had it. But if I were to do it again, I wouldn’t use gel (just a preference thing, it turned out fine).

Shared more details and a supplies list on Paper and Stitch today. And in case you’re wondering what happened to the old base… good news! I left it outside with a note on what it could be turned into and someone picked it up right away to reuse.
